rrChassisMaxSlots.description: Maximum number of slots in the chassis.

rrChassisNumCards.description: Number of cards detected in the chassis.

rrChassisSlotId.description: The chassis slot of the card.

rrChassisSlotSwVer.name: rrChassisSlotSwVer
rrChassisSlotSwVer.description: The card IPMI (Intelligent Platform Management Interface) firmware version number.

phyAiuExcessiveFakeAid.name: phyAiuExcessiveFakeAid
phyAiuExcessiveFakeAid.description: This object is true(1) if the assembly ID is programmed under more than one source.

phyAiuRebootRr.name: phyAiuRebootRr
phyAiuRebootRr.description: Setting this object to true(1) will power cycle the RadioRouter chassis!

phyMcuExcessiveFakeAid.description: This object is true if the assembly ID is programmed under more than one source.

phyBbuExcessiveFakeAid.description: This object is true if the assembly ID is programmed under more than one source.

phyRxuExcessiveFakeAid.name: phyRxuExcessiveFakeAid
phyRxuExcessiveFakeAid.description: This object is true if the assembly ID is programmed under more than one source.

phyTxuExcessiveFakeAid.name: phyTxuExcessiveFakeAid
phyTxuExcessiveFakeAid.description: This object is true if the assembly ID is programmed under more than one source.

paOpState.name: paOpState
paOpState.description: PA operational state. This object is deprecated in favor of paOperStatus.

paOutputTxPower.name: paOutputTxPower
paOutputTxPower.description: PA output transmit power, in dbm.

paInputTxPower.name: paInputTxPower
paInputTxPower.description: PA input transmit power, in dbm.

paTxReflectedPower.name: paTxReflectedPower
paTxReflectedPower.description: PA transmit reflected power, in dbm.

paDcPowerFault.name: paDcPowerFault
paDcPowerFault.description: This object indicates if a PA DC power fault exists.

paRfOverdriveFault.name: paRfOverdriveFault
paRfOverdriveFault.description: This object indicates if a PA RF overdrive fault exists.

paFeedForwardFault.name: paFeedForwardFault
paFeedForwardFault.description: This object indicates if a PA feed forward fault exists.

paRfBand.name: paRfBand
paRfBand.description: PA RF band. This object is deprecated in favor of paRadioFreqBand.

paReflectedPowerFault.name: paReflectedPowerFault
paReflectedPowerFault.description: This object indicates if a reflected power fault exists.

paUnderPowerFault.name: paUnderPowerFault
paUnderPowerFault.description: This object indicates if an under power fault exists.

paFanSpeedOk.name: paFanSpeedOk
paFanSpeedOk.description: This object indicates if the PA shelf fan speed is within normal operating limits.

paFanTempOk.name: paFanTempOk
paFanTempOk.description: This object indicates if the PA shelf fan temperature is within normal operating limits.

paBreakerTripped.name: paBreakerTripped
paBreakerTripped.description: This object indicates if a PA shelf breaker has been tripped.

paSimulcast.name: paSimulcast
paSimulcast.description: This object indicates if the PA shelf supports simulcast.

paTxCalEnabled.name: paTxCalEnabled
paTxCalEnabled.description: This object indicates if PX Gain control loop is enabled.

paPowerTable.name: paPowerTable
paPowerTable.description: This table is used to display PA various Tx power values. These values are store on the system as floating point numbers, but since SNMP cannot display floating point numbers, this table will convert the values to integer.

paPowerTxOutput.name: paPowerTxOutput
paPowerTxOutput.description: PA output Tx power. In order to retain precision in converting the floating point value into integer, the value is first multiplied by 100. For example 43.25dB will be represented as 4325.

paPowerTxInput.name: paPowerTxInput
paPowerTxInput.description: PA input Tx power. In order to retain precision in converting the floating point value into integer, the value is first multiplied by 100. For example -50.75dB will be represented as -5075.

paPowerTxReflected.name: paPowerTxReflected
paPowerTxReflected.description: PA reflected Tx power. In order to retain precision in converting the floating point value into integer, the value is first multiplied by 100. For example 21.00dB will be represented as 2100.

bbuSysEntry.name: bbuSysEntry
bbuSysEntry.description: Base Band Unit system table entry.

bbuSysId.name: bbuSysId
bbuSysId.description: This identifies a single BBU in a basestation.

bbuDspVer.name: bbuDspVer
bbuDspVer.description: The read-only statistic indicates the version number of the DSP software currently operational on the sector in question. It has the major.minor.micro notation.

bbuLlcVer.name: bbuLlcVer
bbuLlcVer.description: The read-only statistic indicates the version number of the Link List Controller software/firmware currently operational on the sector in question. It has the major.minor notation.

bbuTxFpgaVer.name: bbuTxFpgaVer
bbuTxFpgaVer.description: The read-only statistic indicates the version number of the Tx FPGA software/firmware currently operational on the sector in question. It has the major.minor notation.

bbuRxFpgaVer.name: bbuRxFpgaVer
bbuRxFpgaVer.description: The read-only statistic indicates the version number of the Rx FPGA software/firmware currently operational on the sector in question. It has the major.minor notation.

bbuLdpcVer.name: bbuLdpcVer
bbuLdpcVer.description: The read-only statistic indicates the version number of the LDPC encoder/decoder software/firmware currently operational on the sector in question. It has the major.minor notation.

bbuRfChanNum.name: bbuRfChanNum
bbuRfChanNum.description: The RF channel number, in conjunction with the bbuRffBand object defines the frequency of operation. The channel number follows well-known ITU numbering, and represents 50 kHz spacing. The step size depends on the band. In the 1.9 GHz band, the step size is 4 (200 kHz). Editable offline.

bbuExtGainTx.name: bbuExtGainTx
bbuExtGainTx.description: Represents the total external gain in the Tx path. Typically it equals PA gain minus any attenuators. The value is in dB * 32 (scaled by 32). E.g., default value is 43 dB, which is the PA gain, and is represented as 43*32 = 1376. This parameter is used to assist the mobile in making an access attempt at an appropriate power level. The step size is 1 dB. Editable online.

bbuExtGainRx.name: bbuExtGainRx
bbuExtGainRx.description: Represents the total external gain in the Rx path. Typically it equals LNA gain minus any attenuators. The value is in dB * 32 (scaled by 32). E.g., default value is 31 dB, which is the LNA gain, and is represented as 31*32 = 992. This parameter is used to assist the mobile in making an access attempt at an appropriate power level. The step size is 1 dB. Editable online.

bbuRfGainRx0.name: bbuRfGainRx0
bbuRfGainRx0.description: Represents the gain (in dB) provided by the RF Rx blade(RXU) in the Rx0 path. This gain is in addition to the gain provided by the LNA. This value is typically calibrated and set in the factory. The step size is 1 dB. Editable online.

bbuRfGainRx1.name: bbuRfGainRx1
bbuRfGainRx1.description: Represents the gain (in dB) provided by the RF Rx blade(RXU) in the Rx1 path. This gain is in addition to the gain provided by the LNA. This value is typically calibrated and set in the factory. The step size is 1 dB. Editable online.

bbuRfBand.name: bbuRfBand
bbuRfBand.description: The band of operation, represented by an enumeration. E.g., the 1.9 GHz PCS band has a value of 6, while the 2.1 GHz UMTS band has a value of 7. This quantity, in conjunction with the bbuRfChanNum decides the frequency of operation. Editable offline.

bbuRfPowerTx0.name: bbuRfPowerTx0
bbuRfPowerTx0.description: Represents the signal strength in dBm of the Tx signal put out on Tx0 by the TXU. An increase in this implies an increase in the signal input to the PA. Step size is 1 dBm. Editable online.

bbuRfPowerTx1.name: bbuRfPowerTx1
bbuRfPowerTx1.description: Represents the signal strength in dBm of the Tx signal put out on Tx1 by the TXU. An increase in this implies an increase in the signal input to the PA. Step size is 1 dBm. Editable online.

bbuRfuEnableMask.name: bbuRfuEnableMask
bbuRfuEnableMask.description: This is a bit mask to choose between the 0 and 1 channels for Rx and Tx. The value should be an OR of the channels selected, where: Tx0 = 0001 Tx1 = 0010 Rx0 = 0100 Rx1 = 1000 For example, set this object to 6 if Rx0 and Tx1 need to be enabled.

bbuExtTxGain.name: bbuExtTxGain
bbuExtTxGain.description: External Tx gain. Valid range is -50.0 to 70.0.

bbuExtRxGain.name: bbuExtRxGain
bbuExtRxGain.description: External Rx gain. Valid range is -50.0 to 70.0.

bbuRfRx0Gain.name: bbuRfRx0Gain
bbuRfRx0Gain.description: Represents the gain (in dB) provided by the RF Rx blade(RXU) in the Rx0 path. This gain is in addition to the gain provided by the LNA. This value is typically calibrated and set in the factory. The step size is 1 dB. Valid range is -10.0 to 75.0. Editable online.

bbuRfRx1Gain.name: bbuRfRx1Gain
bbuRfRx1Gain.description: Represents the gain (in dB) provided by the RF Rx blade(RXU) in the Rx1 path. This gain is in addition to the gain provided by the LNA. This value is typically calibrated and set in the factory. The step size is 1 dB. Valid range is -10.0 to 75.0. Editable online.

bbuRfTx0Power.name: bbuRfTx0Power
bbuRfTx0Power.description: Represents the signal strength in dBm of the Tx signal put out on Tx0 by the TXU. An increase in this implies an increase in the signal input to the PA. Step size is 1 dBm. Valid range is -20.0 to 10.0. Editable online.

bbuRfTx1Power.name: bbuRfTx1Power
bbuRfTx1Power.description: Represents the signal strength in dBm of the Tx signal put out on Tx1 by the TXU. An increase in this implies an increase in the signal input to the PA. Step size is 1 dBm. Valid range is -20.0 to 10.0. Editable online.

bbuSlope.name: bbuSlope
bbuSlope.description: Represents the slope of the RR sector. It is an identifier which allows a mobile to distinguish between signals from different basestations. There are 112 possible slope values, however, only 80 of these are considered valid values. Editable offline.

bbuSleepInactivityTimer.name: bbuSleepInactivityTimer
bbuSleepInactivityTimer.description: Represents the amount of time of data inactivity (on the forward or reverse links) after which a mobile moves to the Sleep state. In units of 1/3 seconds [ eg. Value = 180 represents 60 seconds]. This time period is conveyed to the mobile at the time of establishing connectivity with the basestation. This quantity is non-linearly quantized, so the actual duration of inactivity before sleep may be slightly different from this value. Step size is 1/3 second. Range is 0 to 20 minutes. 0 means never go to sleep. Recommended value is 180 (i.e., 60sec). Editable online.

bbuLuTimer.name: bbuLuTimer
bbuLuTimer.description: Periodicity, in seconds, of location update done by a stationary mobile. This time period is conveyed to the mobile at the time of establishing connectivity with the RR. This quantity is non-linearly quantized, so the actual duration of location update may be slightly different from this value. Step size is 1 second. Range is 5 seconds to 18 hours. Editable online.
